## Thread.Abort â†’ Cooperative Cancellation Migration

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that **will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8**:

| Found API | Location | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue execution after abort |

### Key paradigm shift

.NET Framework used **preemptive** cancellation â€” the runtime injected `ThreadAbortException` at arbitrary points. .NET 8 requires **cooperative** cancellation â€” your code must voluntarily check a `CancellationToken` and respond.

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);       // pass token for checkpoint checks
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch:
                // clean up partial work, then exit the loop gracefully.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed â€” we control whether to continue or break.
                // In this case we break because cancellation was requested.
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token â€” replaces Thread.Abort()

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. In .NET 8 there is NO way to
            // forcibly kill it. Log a warning â€” see pitfalls below.
            // If this is a real risk, move uncooperative work to a child process.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitOne`, `Task.Delay`, async I/O) â€” a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal; abort throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed â€” just `break` or continue | You control the loop; no runtime-injected rethrow to suppress |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then abort | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Waits *for the thread*, not just wall-clock time |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed |

---

### Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem()` must cooperate

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection`, socket, or `ManualResetEvent`), cancellation **will not interrupt it** unless you pass the token through:

```csharp
// âťŚ Will NOT respond to cancellation â€” thread stays blocked
var item = _queue.Take();

// âś… Throws OperationCanceledException when token is cancelled
var item = _queue.Take(token);

// âś… For WaitHandle-based blocking:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });

// âś… For Thread.Sleep replacements:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // wakes on cancel
```

**This is the #1 migration failure mode.** If any method in the call chain ignores the token, `Stop()` will hang at `Join()` and you have no fallback (no `Thread.Abort` to force it).

---

### Other pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** | Let it propagate except at the top-level loop. The `break` above is intentional â€” don't just swallow and continue. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `Dispose()` â€” it leaks timer handles. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` does 30 seconds of CPU work with no token check, cancellation waits 30 seconds. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long operations. |
| **No fallback for truly uncooperative code** | If you call third-party code that can't accept a token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` â€” that's the only .NET 8 equivalent of a hard abort. |
